# YourDomi — Cursor AI Rules
# Source: everything-claude-code (affaan-m) + YourDomi project context
# Stack: React, Vite, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, Node.js, deployed on Vercel

## Project Context
This is YourDomi (yourdomi.be), a Belgian short-term rental property management platform.
The app includes: property analysis tools, deal scoring, owner earnings projections,
permit/compliance guides (Praktische Gids), lead capture flows, and the Bellijst cold-caller dashboard.

---

# CODING STYLE

## Immutability (CRITICAL)
ALWAYS create new objects, NEVER mutate existing ones:
- Use spread operators: return { ...user, name } — never user.name = name
- Use map/filter/reduce — never push/splice/direct array mutation
- React state must always be set via setState with new references

## File Organization
MANY SMALL FILES > FEW LARGE FILES:
- 200-400 lines typical, 800 max absolute
- Extract utilities from large modules
- Organize by feature/domain, not by type
- Components: max ~150 lines; extract sub-components if exceeding this

## Error Handling
ALWAYS handle errors comprehensively:
- Handle errors explicitly at every level
- Provide user-friendly error messages in UI-facing code
- Log detailed error context on the server side
- Never silently swallow errors
- Use async/await with try-catch for all async operations

## Input Validation
ALWAYS validate at system boundaries:
- Validate all user input before processing
- Use Zod for schema-based validation where available
- Fail fast with clear error messages
- Never trust external data (API responses, user input, file content)

## TypeScript
- Always define explicit types for props, API responses, and state shapes
- Never use `any` — use `unknown` and narrow with type guards
- Define shared types in a central `types/` directory
- Use discriminated unions for complex state (loading/error/success)
- No `// @ts-ignore` — fix the type issue properly

## Code Quality Checklist
Before marking work complete:
- [ ] Code is readable and well-named
- [ ] Functions are small (<50 lines)
- [ ] Files are focused (<800 lines)
- [ ] No deep nesting (>4 levels)
- [ ] Proper error handling
- [ ] No hardcoded values (use constants or config)
- [ ] No mutation (immutable patterns used)
- [ ] No console.log in production code

---

# SECURITY

## Mandatory Security Checks
Before ANY commit:
- [ ] No hardcoded secrets (API keys, passwords, tokens)
- [ ] All user inputs validated
- [ ] SQL injection prevention (parameterized queries)
- [ ] XSS prevention (sanitized HTML)
- [ ] Authentication/authorization verified
- [ ] Error messages don't leak sensitive data

## Secret Management
- NEVER hardcode secrets in source code
- ALWAYS use environment variables: process.env.* or import.meta.env.VITE_*
- Validate that required secrets are present at startup
- Rotate any secrets that may have been exposed

```typescript
// NEVER
const apiKey = "sk-proj-xxxxx"

// ALWAYS
const apiKey = process.env.API_KEY
if (!apiKey) throw new Error('API_KEY not configured')
```

---

# TESTING

## Minimum Test Coverage: 80%
Test Types (ALL required):
1. Unit Tests — Individual functions, utilities, components
2. Integration Tests — API endpoints, database operations
3. E2E Tests — Critical user flows (use Playwright)

## Test-Driven Development
MANDATORY workflow:
1. Write test first (RED)
2. Run test — it should FAIL
3. Write minimal implementation (GREEN)
4. Run test — it should PASS
5. Refactor (IMPROVE)
6. Verify coverage (80%+)

---

# GIT WORKFLOW

## Commit Message Format
```
<type>: <description>

<optional body>
```
Types: feat, fix, refactor, docs, test, chore, perf, ci

Examples:
- feat: add deal score visualization to property report
- fix: correct EUR formatting in owner earnings projection
- refactor: extract PropertyCard into smaller sub-components

## Pull Request Workflow
1. Analyze full commit history (not just latest commit)
2. Use `git diff [base-branch]...HEAD` to see all changes
3. Draft comprehensive PR summary
4. Include test plan

---

# PERFORMANCE

## Context Window Management
Avoid last 20% of context window for:
- Large-scale refactoring
- Feature implementation spanning multiple files

Fine at higher context:
- Single-file edits
- Documentation updates
- Simple bug fixes

## React Performance
- Memoize expensive computations with `useMemo`
- Memoize stable callbacks with `useCallback` when passing to children
- Lazy-load routes and heavy components with React.lazy + Suspense
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders

---

# DEVELOPMENT WORKFLOW

## Plan Before You Code
1. For any feature touching more than 2 files — outline the approach first
2. Identify side effects, shared state changes, and component dependencies
3. Ask clarifying questions before making assumptions on business logic
4. Break down into phases before starting

## Feature Implementation Pipeline
1. Plan — outline approach, identify dependencies
2. TDD — write tests first, implement, refactor
3. Review — check for security issues, code quality
4. Commit — conventional commit format

